>>20352887

I mean, there's a couple of decent new-ish Authors that you could read that are pretty decent if you're not looking for Mary Sues or cardboard characters:

Tious: Only has 'Rainy Day' but it's super comfy. Story is hilariously simple, but it works the topic well.

Pixelated_Hobo: Latest thing is Preferred treatment. He's not to the point where there's lewds yet, but it seems like it'll be promising. All his other stuff is good, but if you want patrician lewds (and maybe a bit of a Mary Sue) check out 'Tough to Love'

Bed-Man has 'Myrrah's Hunters'. Outside of a story that's begging for some Awoo Lewd, it's a pretty nicely fleshed out little world whose characters have some depth and writing that maintains good perspective.

Jack_Dawe only has 'The Wolf and the Huntsman' out. Dude is slow AF to update, but it seems comfy enough. Awoo waifu could be considered a bit of a Mary Sue, but that gets balanced out in the interplay with the main.

Sham has a shit load of comfy-af little stories. Not exactly hero's epics, but that's not really what we're here to read. I happen to like 'Hell-o Nurse' in particular, as it's a lot like Nightmare before Christmas without Tim Burton fellating Johnny Depp.

Decofox has Silver Lining which is a welcome spin on the Buck Rodgers style pulp action. Told from the perspective of the aforementioned chisel chinned protagonist, who turns out not to feel at all like others portray him. nice juxtaposition, good story, and cool little concept.

There's a shit ton more, but those are the ones that jump out at me as having a bit more nuance.
